Date: Sun 18 Dec 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Columbian, Clark County WA [edited]
<http://www.columbian.com/news/localNews/12182005news70224.cfm>

5 more cases of _E. coli_ linked to dairy's raw milk
-----------------------------------------------
Interviews with consumers of raw milk from Dee Creek Farm have turned up 5
more people sickened with _E. coli_ (O157), public health officials said
Sat 17 Dec 2005.
The new cases bring the total sickened to 17 people, including 2 children
still in critical condition. None of the cases -- announced Sat 17 Dec 2005
and discovered in 3 children and 2 adults -- required hospitalization,
officials said.
A Cowlitz County judge had ordered farmers Anita and Michael Puckett to
turn over the names of 45 families who obtained raw, or unpasteurized, milk
from the Woodland farm.
State laboratory results showed a bacterial DNA match between the 1st
confirmed case of _E. coli_ and 3 other cases, said Marni Storey, Clark
County's public health manager. That match proves the cases are linked and
also points to Dee Creek Farm as the source of the outbreak, Storey said.
"100 percent of the people with _E. coli_ reported consuming unpasteurized
milk from Dee Creek dairy," Storey said. "There's a very strong association
between the milk and these illnesses."
Summer Steenbarger, the Pucketts' daughter, said Thu 15 Dec 2005 that 3
farm workers sought medical attention for diarrhea at the time the _E.
coli_ cases began to surface but said their symptoms were not severe enough
to warrant testing. In August 2005, the Washington Department of
Agriculture ordered Dee Creek Farm to stop selling raw milk because it did
not have a license, but the Pucketts denied selling raw milk. They were,
however, continuing to distribute raw milk through a system of shared
ownership in cows housed at the farm.
Cow-sharing arrangements are not illegal, state agricultural officials have
said, but they cannot be used as a loophole to laws that ban distribution
of raw milk without a license. Steenbarger, who has said the farm now plans
to seek a license, said Dee Creek's milk has tested clean 3 times in recent
weeks. She suggested that consumers of the milk were somehow responsible
for their condition and that the cases occurred coincidentally.
On Sat 17 Dec 2005, Storey did not assert an absolute link between the milk
and the _E. coli_ cases based on the DNA tests. She said further lab
results are expected next week. Of the 2 children still in critical
condition, Storey said one was still on life support and the other's health
was improving slightly. She declined to reveal where the children are
hospitalized, citing privacy concerns.
[Byline: Justin Carinci]
