Date: Fri 16 Dec 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Daily News, Longview, WA [edited]
<http://www.tdn.com/articles/2005/12/17/area_news/news02.txt>

21 possible cases of _E.coli_ reported
-------------------------------------------
The number of suspected or confirmed _E. coli_ (O157) cases now stands at
21, after health officials gained access Fri 16 Dec 2005 to the Dee Creek
Farm's customer list. The farm owners, Anita and Michael Puckett of
Woodland, turned the list over at 10:29 p.m. on Thursday [15 Dec 2005].
Cowlitz County obtained a court order Thursday afternoon giving the family
24 hours to release the names of the people who drank the unpasteurized, or
raw, milk the farm produces.
45 families -- including the Pucketts -- were on the list. The families,
called co-owners by the Pucketts, live in Cowlitz and Clark counties in
Washington and Clatsop, Multnomah and Wasco counties in Oregon. Local
health officials spent the day contacting the families in their counties,
and 7 new suspected cases were discovered, 4 in Cowlitz County and 3 in
Clark County. Suspected cases mean a person drank the suspect milk and has
symptoms but has not yet been tested.
Also Fri 16 Dec 2005, a new confirmed case was announced in Clark County,
bringing the number of confirmed or suspected cases in that county to 11.
Cowlitz County has 7 suspected or confirmed cases, and 3 people in Clatsop
County are being tested.
Of the 5 Clark County children hospitalized with _E. coli_, 2 remain in the
hospital. One of those was said to be improving, according to Clark County.
Both were still listed as being in critical condition, and Clark County
Health Department officials said they did not know whether the children
were still on life support.
Health officials will continue contacting any families they couldn't reach
on Fri 16 Dec 2005 during the weekend.
[Byline: Barbara LaBoe]
